"## Abstract\nLight field depth estimation is fundamental to 3D vision applications. However, accurately recovering depth in complex scenes with mixed reflectance properties remains a formidable challenge. Existing epipolar plane image (EPI) methods heavily rely on the Lambertian assumption, severely degrading when physical constraints are violated by non-Lambertian surfaces. To address this, we proposed a Unified Dual-Mask Physical Model that decoupled illumination, depth, and material properties via a three-layer angular signal decomposition. Specifically, the angular signal was factorized into DC, linear, and residual components, which enabled the extraction of highly discriminative geometric features, such as angular gradients, to replace traditional spectral analysis. Furthermore, an adaptive geometric dual-mask routing architecture dynamically directed Lambertian and non-Lambertian regions to specialized branches, and the network was optimized via a staged training strategy incorporating guided training and domain-balanced sampling. Extensive experiments demonstrate that our method achieves an overall mean absolute error (MAE) of 0.133 and an exceptional MAE of 0.081 in complex mixed and urban scenarios, significantly outperforming state-of-the-art baselines. This work establishes a robust physical foundation for unified light field depth estimation, effectively overcoming the inherent limitations of conventional EPI models in non-Lambertian environments.\n\n**Keywords:** Light field depth estimation, Non-Lambertian surfaces, Angular signal decomposition, Dual-mask routing, Epipolar plane image"